    <subsection xml:id="definitions-rational-functions">
        <title>Definitions</title>
        <definition>
            <title>Rational Function</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A <term>rational function</term> is a function that can be written as the quotient of two polynomial functions, where the denominator is not 0.
                    <me>r(x)=\dfrac{p(x)}{q(x)}</me>
                    where <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are polynomial functions and <m>q(x)\neq0</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <definition>
            <title>Vertical Asymptotes</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Given a function <m>f</m> and a real number <m>a</m>, a <term>vertical asymptote</term> of the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> is a vertical line <m>x=a</m> where <m>f(x)</m> tends toward positive or negative infinity as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from either the left or the right. We write this as:
                    <me>\text{As } x \to a^{-}, f(x) \to \pm \infty \text{ or as } x \to a^{+}, f(x) \to \infty.</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <example>
            <p>
                <m>x=1</m> is a vertical asymptote of <m>f(x)=\dfrac{x-5}{x-1}</m> due to the following:
                <ul>
                    <li>As <m>x</m> approaches <m>x=1</m> from the left, the <m>y</m>-values increase towards <m>\infty</m>. Mathematically, we write this: As <m>x \to 1^{-}, f(x) \to \infty</m>.</li>
                    <li>As <m>x</m> approaches <m>x=1</m> from the right, the <m>y</m>-values decrease towards <m>-\infty</m>. Mathematically, we write this: As <m>x \to 1^{+}, f(x) \to -\infty</m>.</li>
                </ul>
                <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/t10efozl3i" visual="https://tiny.cc/111Z-VertAsymp">View this Desmos graph</url> to see an interactive version of this example.
            </p>
        </example>
        <definition>
            <title>Multiplicity and Vertical Asymptotes</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The multiplicity of a root of the denominator of a rational function impacts the behavior of the vertical asymptote.
                </p>
                <p>
                    If the rational function is factored and reduced to its simplest terms, <term>a root of the denominator with even multiplicity</term> will produce a vertical asymptote that approaches <m>\infty</m> on both sides or that approaches <m>-\infty</m> on both sides.
                </p>
                <p>
                    If the rational function is factored and reduced to its simplest terms, <term>a root of the denominator with odd multiplicity</term> will produce a vertical asymptote that approaches <m>\infty</m> on one side and <m>-\infty</m> on the other.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <example>
            <p>
                <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/u1ed06auqc" visual="https://tiny.cc/111Z-MultiplicityAndVA">View this Desmos graph</url> to see an interactive version of this example.
            </p>
        </example>
        <definition>
            <title>Horizontal Asymptotes</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Given a function <m>f</m> and a real number <m>L</m>, a <term>horizontal asymptote</term> of a graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> is a horizontal line <m>y=L</m> where <m>f(x)</m> tends toward <m>L</m>  as <m>x</m> approaches <m>\infty</m> or as <m>x</m> approaches <m>-\infty</m>. We write this as:
                    <me>\text{As } x \to \infty \text{ or as } x \to -\infty, f(x) \to L.</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <example>
            <p>
                <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/9bqtdmnl4w" visual="http://tiny.cc/111Z-HorizAsymp">View this Desmos graph</url> to see an interactive version of this example.
            </p>
        </example>
	</subsection>
        
